<div class="item-title"><span class="zh">一、AI分身之Second Me & ELYS</span><span class="zht">一、AI分身之Second Me & ELYS</span><span class="en">I. AI Avatars: Second Me & ELYS</span></div>
<div class="item-meta">2026.3</div>
<div class="item-excerpt"><span class="zh">因为喜欢社交网络，喜欢社群平台，喜欢TOC的Agent，所以会用一些AI+社交产品，分身类产品里有两款用得比较深：Mindverse 出的 Second Me，和之前一夜刷屏的 ELYS。Second Me 我打 2/3 好评，ELYS 我打中评。两个都不算"好"，但不到的方式很不一样。行业里把 ELYS 和 Second Me 都归到 "AI 分身"，我觉得这个归类有点偏懒。</span><span class="zht">因為喜歡社交網路，喜歡社群平台，喜歡TOC的Agent，所以會用一些AI+社交產品，分身類產品裡有兩款用得比較深：Mindverse 出的 Second Me，和之前一夜刷屏的 ELYS。Second Me 我打 2/3 好評，ELYS 我打中評。兩個都不算「好」，但不到的方式很不一樣。行業裡把 ELYS 和 Second Me 都歸到「AI 分身」，我覺得這個歸類有點偏懶。</span><span class="en">I've been using AI + social products because I love social networks, community platforms, and ToC agents. Two avatar products stood out: Mindverse's Second Me and the overnight sensation ELYS. I'd give Second Me a 2/3 positive and ELYS a neutral. Neither quite reaches "good," but they fall short in very different ways.</span></div>
<div class="item-full" id="full-0"><span class="zh">因为喜欢社交网络。喜欢社群平台，喜欢TOC的Agent，所以会用一些AI+社交产品，分身类产品里有两款用得比较深：Mindverse 出的 Second Me，和之前一夜刷屏的 ELYS。

Second Me 我打 2/3 好评，ELYS 我打中评。两个都不到"好"，但不到的方式很不一样。行业里把 ELYS 和 Second Me 都归到 "AI 分身"，我觉得这个归类有点偷懒。


Second Me 的底层逻辑是"数字身份主权"——开源、本地训练，分身是你的资产，可以接入到任何场景去代表你。
ELYS 的底层逻辑是"社交代理"——分身 24 小时替你浏览全网、点赞评论、做预交互筛选，关键节点真人接管。
一个试图让你拥有自己，一个试图让你外包自己。


Second Me：概念有意思，但我不知道怎么把它用进生活

数字分身这件事我自己幻想过很多次。它对我来说不只是"别人可以接触到的我"，更是一个关于我如何塑造我自己的人生观问题。所以第一次用 Second Me，看到能跟朋友的分身聊天，那个感觉是有点酷的——而且聊起来真的像本人，看得出来朋友喂了不少东西进去。开源、本地化、把用户身份训成一个可迁移的资产。GitHub 短期 10K+ stars 不是偶然，是因为这套叙事在 AI 时代越来越有人愿意为之投票。

但我还是没法说服自己持续用它。首先是两个直观的问题：一是动态背景。挺多图（尤其是带人脸或动物的）动起来之后是瘆人的，那种"AI 假动"的感觉特别明显，反而让"分身"的可信度受损。二是线下场景。他们有用 NFC 圆片做交友互动，但我用过的同类 NFC 贴纸灵敏度都比这个高（可能只是我那批的偶然问题，但既然是产品的线下触点就值得说一句）。

这两件事单独看都是小问题，合起来看就指向一个更大的疑问：Second Me 想做的是"AI 时代的身份基础设施"，但身份基础设施需要的是稳定、可信、低存在感，不是 demo 感。现在的产品形态在我这里更像一个"概念验证"。
同时还有个用户惯性的问题：分身需要用户的数据，用户的数据更多放在PC端，而社交场景则要依附于移动端

ELYS：把社交做成了 sourcing 机器。优点是：反问式 onboarding。塑造分身的时候它不是让你单方面喂信息，而是不断反问深挖。有些问题问得挺有水平，让我重新想了一下自己。这是我体验过的分身产品里 onboarding 设计最好的；AI 互评 + 真人确认的混合机制。分身浏览、评论、点赞，你来决定哪些 AI 的反应是"对的"。

但它有几个我不喜欢的点：

第一，功能局限。它很想做"精准 match"，但对"人味儿"的理解和它想做的事之间有 gap。我用它就是想 sourcing 更多人，结果出现了几百个分身浏览我但不点赞不评论的情况（甚至在我明确给出"多点赞评论"的微调指令之后还是这样）。

第二，缺乏交付结果。大部分内容还是没网感、没人味儿的堆叠。更重要的是，就算分身帮我"连上"了一个人，我看不到在这个 app 上认识这个人会带来什么——人用一个 app 是要有结果的，LinkedIn 给你工作机会，dating app 给你约会，ELYS 给你什么？现在还不清楚。


第三——这是我最不爽的一点——它强制你选 MBTI。

我真的讨厌贴标签这件事，尤其是用一个被心理学界长期质疑的工具，把一个人压缩成 16 种之一。
而最反讽的是：ELYS 这个产品的整套叙事，是"每个人都是独特的灵魂，我们用 128 个记忆槽位去精细刻画你"。但你的 onboarding 第一步，是让我从 16 个标签里选一个。


这是产品哲学的自相矛盾。如果你真的相信"一个人的灵魂是 ta 所有 context 的总和"（Tristan 自己说的），那 MBTI 应该是用户可以选填、也可以完全跳过的字段，而不是必填项。把 MBTI 设成必填，本质上是承认"我们暂时还做不到从 context 里读你，所以先用一个粗糙的 16 分类兜底"。这件事对一个声称要做下一代社交的产品来说，是个挺刺眼的妥协。



Second Me 在做对的方向，做得不到位：身份主权这件事确实重要，但产品还没找到一个让人愿意每天打开的形态。
ELYS 把执行做到了位，但产品哲学没立住：用 AI 帮人外包社交是个聪明的切入，可一旦你的产品在 onboarding 第一步就贴标签，"做你自己，美好的事情自然奔来"这句 slogan 就变成了营销话术。


对分身类产品，我觉得最重要的是"人格分发"，但是对于如此敏感的1v1，ELYS还是依赖于MBTI等等路径；
对于我想塑造的那个"我"，我最需要的无非就是我在定义我如何塑造分身这件事本身，在这点上不论second me还是ELYS都好像还是在流量时代带着"社交"的镣铐跳舞。</span><span class="zht">因為喜歡社交網絡。喜歡社群平台，喜歡TOC的Agent，所以會用一些AI+社交產品，分身類產品裡有兩款用得比較深：Mindverse 出的 Second Me，和之前一夜刷屏的 ELYS。

Second Me 我打 2/3 好評，ELYS 我打中評。兩個都不到「好」，但不到的方式很不一樣。行業裡把 ELYS 和 Second Me 都歸到「AI 分身」，我覺得這個歸類有點偷懶。


Second Me 的底層邏輯是「數位身份主權」——開源、本地訓練，分身是你的資產，可以接入到任何場景去代表你。
ELYS 的底層邏輯是「社交代理」——分身 24 小時替你瀏覽全網、點讚評論、做預交互篩選，關鍵節點真人接管。
一個試圖讓你擁有自己，一個試圖讓你外包自己。


Second Me：概念有意思，但我不知道怎麼把它用進生活

數位分身這件事我自己幻想過很多次。它對我來說不只是「別人可以接觸到的我」，更是一個關於我如何塑造我自己的人生觀問題。所以第一次用 Second Me，看到能跟朋友的分身聊天，那個感覺是有點酷的——而且聊起來真的像本人，看得出來朋友餵了不少東西進去。開源、本地化、把用戶身份訓成一個可遷移的資產。GitHub 短期 10K+ stars 不是偶然，是因為這套敘事在 AI 時代越來越有人願意為之投票。

但我還是沒法說服自己持續用它。首先是兩個直觀的問題：一是動態背景。挺多圖（尤其是帶人臉或動物的）動起來之後是瘮人的，那種「AI 假動」的感覺特別明顯，反而讓「分身」的可信度受損。二是線下場景。他們有用 NFC 圓片做交友互動，但我用過的同類 NFC 貼紙靈敏度都比這個高（可能只是我那批的偶然問題，但既然是產品的線下觸點就值得說一句）。

這兩件事單獨看都是小問題，合起來看就指向一個更大的疑問：Second Me 想做的是「AI 時代的身份基礎設施」，但身份基礎設施需要的是穩定、可信、低存在感，不是 demo 感。現在的產品形態在我這裡更像一個「概念驗證」。
同時還有個用戶慣性的問題：分身需要用戶的數據，用戶的數據更多放在PC端，而社交場景則要依附於移動端

ELYS：把社交做成了 sourcing 機器。優點是：反問式 onboarding。塑造分身的時候它不是讓你單方面餵資訊，而是不斷反問深挖。有些問題問得挺有水準，讓我重新想了一下自己。這是我體驗過的分身產品裡 onboarding 設計最好的；AI 互評 + 真人確認的混合機制。分身瀏覽、評論、點讚，你來決定哪些 AI 的反應是「對的」。

但它有幾個我不喜歡的點：

第一，功能局限。它很想做「精準 match」，但對「人味兒」的理解和它想做的事之間有 gap。我用它就是想 sourcing 更多人，結果出現了幾百個分身瀏覽我但不點讚不評論的情況（甚至在我明確給出「多點讚評論」的微調指令之後還是這樣）。

第二，缺乏交付結果。大部分內容還是沒網感、沒人味兒的堆疊。更重要的是，就算分身幫我「連上」了一個人，我看不到在這個 app 上認識這個人會帶來什麼——人用一個 app 是要有結果的，LinkedIn 給你工作機會，dating app 給你約會，ELYS 給你什麼？現在還不清楚。


第三——這是我最不爽的一點——它強制你選 MBTI。

我真的討厭貼標籤這件事，尤其是用一個被心理學界長期質疑的工具，把一個人壓縮成 16 種之一。
而最反諷的是：ELYS 這個產品的整套敘事，是「每個人都是獨特的靈魂，我們用 128 個記憶槽位去精細刻畫你」。但你的 onboarding 第一步，是讓我從 16 個標籤裡選一個。


這是產品哲學的自相矛盾。如果你真的相信「一個人的靈魂是 ta 所有 context 的總和」（Tristan 自己說的），那 MBTI 應該是用戶可以選填、也可以完全跳過的字段，而不是必填項。把 MBTI 設成必填，本質上是承認「我們暫時還做不到從 context 裡讀你，所以先用一個粗糙的 16 分類兜底」。這件事對一個聲稱要做下一代社交的產品來說，是個挺刺眼的妥協。



Second Me 在做對的方向，做得不到位：身份主權這件事確實重要，但產品還沒找到一個讓人願意每天打開的形態。
ELYS 把執行做到了位，但產品哲學沒立住：用 AI 幫人外包社交是個聰明的切入，可一旦你的產品在 onboarding 第一步就貼標籤，「做你自己，美好的事情自然奔來」這句 slogan 就變成了行銷話術。


對分身類產品，我覺得最重要的是「人格分發」，但是對於如此敏感的1v1，ELYS還是依賴於MBTI等等路徑；
對於我想塑造的那個「我」，我最需要的無非就是我在定義我如何塑造分身這件事本身，在這點上不論second me還是ELYS都好像還是在流量時代帶著「社交」的鐐銬跳舞。</span><span class="en">I'm into social networks. I like community platforms, I like consumer-facing agents, so naturally I use a bunch of AI + social products. Among the "digital clone" category, there are two I've gone pretty deep with: Mindverse's Second Me, and ELYS — which blew up overnight a while back.

I'd give Second Me a 2-out-of-3 positive rating, and ELYS a middling one. Neither hits "good," but they fall short in very different ways. The industry lumps ELYS and Second Me together under "AI clones," but I think that categorization is lazy.


Second Me's core logic is "digital identity sovereignty" — open source, locally trained, your clone is your asset, deployable across any context to represent you.
ELYS's core logic is "social proxy" — your clone browses the internet 24/7, likes and comments on your behalf, pre-screens interactions, and you take over at key moments.
One tries to let you own yourself. The other tries to let you outsource yourself.


Second Me: Cool concept, but I have no idea how to make it part of my life

I've fantasized about having a digital clone many times. For me it's not just about "a version of me that others can interact with" — it's a worldview question about how I shape who I am. So the first time I used Second Me and saw I could chat with a friend's clone, that felt pretty cool — and the conversation genuinely felt like talking to the real person. You could tell my friend had fed it a lot of material. Open source, local-first, training your identity into a portable asset. Getting 10K+ GitHub stars in a short time wasn't a fluke — it's because this narrative is one that more and more people in the AI era are willing to vote for.

But I still can't convince myself to keep using it. There are two immediate problems: first, the animated backgrounds. A lot of the images (especially ones with human faces or animals) look creepy when animated — that "AI fake motion" feeling is super obvious, and it actually undermines the credibility of the "clone." Second, the offline experience. They use NFC discs for in-person networking, but every similar NFC sticker I've used has been more responsive than theirs (might just be a bad batch on my end, but since it's the product's offline touchpoint, it's worth mentioning).

Each of these is a minor issue on its own, but together they point to a bigger question: Second Me wants to be "identity infrastructure for the AI era," but identity infrastructure needs to be stable, trustworthy, and low-profile — not demo-like. The current product feels more like a proof of concept to me.
There's also a user habit problem: the clone needs user data, which mostly lives on desktop, while social use cases depend on mobile.

ELYS: It turned social networking into a sourcing machine. The upside: reflective onboarding. When building your clone, it doesn't just have you dump information one-way — it keeps asking probing follow-up questions. Some of the questions are genuinely sharp and made me rethink things about myself. Best onboarding design I've seen in any clone product. Plus the hybrid mechanism of AI mutual reviews + human confirmation — the clone browses, comments, and likes, and you decide which of the AI's reactions are "right."

But there are a few things I don't like:

First, limited functionality. It really wants to do "precise matching," but there's a gap between its understanding of "human touch" and what it's trying to achieve. I was using it to source more people, but ended up with hundreds of clones browsing my profile without liking or commenting (even after I explicitly gave fine-tuning instructions to "like and comment more").

Second, no deliverable outcomes. Most of the content is still generic, internet-tone-deaf filler with no personality. More importantly, even if the clone "connects" me with someone, I can't see what knowing this person on this app would lead to — people use an app for outcomes. LinkedIn gives you job opportunities, a dating app gives you dates. What does ELYS give you? Still unclear.


Third — and this is the one that bugs me most — it forces you to pick an MBTI type.

I genuinely hate labeling, especially using a tool that's been questioned by the psychology community for ages, compressing a person into one of 16 types.
And the most ironic part: ELYS's entire product narrative is "every person is a unique soul, and we use 128 memory slots to meticulously portray you." But the very first step of your onboarding is making me pick one of 16 labels.


This is a philosophical contradiction in the product. If you truly believe "a person's soul is the sum of all their context" (Tristan's own words), then MBTI should be an optional field users can fill in or skip entirely — not a required one. Making MBTI mandatory is essentially admitting "we can't actually read you from context yet, so we're falling back on a crude 16-way classification." For a product that claims to be building next-gen social, that's a pretty glaring compromise.



Second Me is heading in the right direction but not executing well enough: identity sovereignty genuinely matters, but the product hasn't found a form that makes people want to open it every day.
ELYS nailed the execution but the product philosophy doesn't hold up: using AI to outsource social interactions is a smart angle, but once your product slaps a label on users at the very first onboarding step, the slogan "be yourself, and beautiful things will come to you" becomes nothing more than marketing copy.


For clone products, I think the most important thing is "personality distribution" — but for something as sensitive as 1-on-1 interaction, ELYS still relies on MBTI and similar shortcuts.
As for the "me" I want to shape, what I need most is simply the act of defining how I build my own clone. And on that front, neither Second Me nor ELYS seems to have broken free — they're still dancing in shackles labeled "social," stuck in the traffic-era mindset.</span></div>
